{"id":"327787520_Circuit_Robustness_to_Temperature_Perturbation_Is_Altered_by_Neuromodulators","abstract":"In the ocean, the crab Cancer borealis is subject to daily and seasonal temperature changes. Previous work, done in the presence of descending modulatory inputs, had shown that the pyloric rhythm of the crab increases in frequency as temperature increases but maintains its characteristic phase relationships until it \"crashes\" at extremely high temperatures. To study the interaction between neuromodulators and temperature perturbations, we studied the effects of temperature on preparations from which the descending modulatory inputs were removed. Under these conditions, the pyloric rhythm was destabilized. We then studied the effects of temperature on preparations in the presence of oxotremorine, proctolin, and serotonin. Oxotremorine and proctolin enhanced the robustness of the pyloric rhythm, whereas serotonin made the rhythm less robust. These experiments reveal considerable animal-to-animal diversity in their crash stability, consistent with the interpretation that cryptic differences in many cell and network parameters are revealed by extreme perturbations.","authors":["Sara Haddad","Eve Marder"],"meta":["September 2018Neuron 100(3)","DOI:10.1016/j.neuron.2018.08.035"],"references":["316523737_Activation_mechanism_of_a_neuromodulator-gated_pacemaker_ionic_current","301792686_Voltage_Dependence_of_a_Neuromodulator-Activated_Ionic_Current","296478816_Functional_Segregation_of_Cortical_Regions_Underlying_Speech_Timing_and_Articulation","288001043_Variability_in_cardiac_electrophysiology_Using_experimentally-calibrated_populations_of_models_to_move_beyond_the_single_virtual_physiological_human_paradigm","282351682_Neuromodulation_to_the_Rescue_Compensation_of_Temperature-Induced_Breakdown_of_Rhythmic_Motor_Patterns_via_Extrinsic_Neuromodulatory_Input","279967300_Consequences_of_acute_and_long-term_removal_of_neuromodulatory_input_on_the_episodic_gastric_rhyth